i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=raystonn>Raystonn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Defender</span><br>  Posts: 507<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/28/03 12:53:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=26302.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: overpowering</span><hr size=1> While being 'buff-like', these spells really aren't buffs.  The durations are such that it would require you to be actively grouped for them to do any good.  You could not sell them in the Bazaar.  As far as enchanters go, they specialize in long-duration buffs/debuffs.  They do not specialize in combat or offense.  That is the forte of a wizard.  Wizards channel their mana into destructive forces.  In this case, the destructive force is stored in another's weapon for a short duration and unleashed as the weapon strikes.  This is very much in character and is nothing like other buffs.<br>
<br>
Enchanters and shamen get 'haste' and 'slow'.  Wizards would get short-duration proxy-damage attacks that only work offensively rather than defensively (defensive meaning something like a damage shield).  The tank would be our proxy to inflict the damage, which would also allow us to avoid aggro issues as the tank would receive the aggro as well.<br>
<br>
Much the same way Gandalf cast spells into his sword and then struck at the Balrog, we could do very similar things.<br>
<br>
-Raystonn<br>
