So you're saying that in order for something to be classified as a buff, it has to be able to be sold as a service?  That's very incorrect, Raystonn. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   A buff is any beneficial spell that can be cast on a player, either self or targetable.  Using your definition Avatar is not a buff, but we know it is.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As far as enchanters go, they specialize in long-duration buffs/debuffs. They do not specialize in combat or offense. That is the forte of a wizard. Wizards channel their mana into destructive forces. In this case, the destructive force is stored in another's weapon for a short duration and unleashed as the weapon strikes. This is very much in character and is nothing like other buffs.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
This falls under the &quot;enchantment&quot; catagory of buffs which most certainly is an Enchanter characteristic.  Our forte is not increasing the damage output of others, but doing massive ammounts of damage by ourselves.  By definition, Wizards are a very self reliant class; not a supporting one.  This spell does indeed play a support role which is very un-Wizard-like.  I'd also like to add that Enchanters specialize more in short duration debuffs (mez and charm), have a focus on increasing group damage (by haste and debuffs) as well as one on mitigating damage (runes, slow, cripple).<br>
<br>
I think this line would make me want to solo more than group.  I think back to the days when my Cleric's buffs didn't last 2.5 hours and there were 3 of them to cast... uggggggh!<br>
<br>
